<BaseLayout
  title="Med-Surgical 2 — Wallace Peterson"
  description="Unfolding case study: Pneumonia with Acute Respiratory Distress and Oxygen Delivery (MED-02)"
>

  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/`}>Cases</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/med-surgical/`}>Med-Surgical</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>Med-Surgical 2 — Wallace Peterson</span>
  </div>

  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">Respiratory / COPD</span>
    <h1>Med-Surgical 2 — Wallace Peterson</h1>
    <p class="case-subtitle">Pneumonia with Acute Respiratory Distress and Oxygen Delivery</p>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>👤 Wallace Peterson, 69 years, Male</span>
      <span>⏱ Scenario: 20–25 minutes</span>
      <span>💬 Debrief: 20–25 minutes</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <strong>📖 How to Use This Unfolding Case Study</strong>
    <p>Work through each phase in order. Information is revealed progressively — exactly as it would be in a real clinical encounter. Before reading each answer, pause and reason through the question yourself. Use the <strong>▶ Reveal Answer</strong> toggles to check your thinking.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- PHASE 1 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase1">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 1</span>
      <h2>You Arrive at the Bedside</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You are the nurse on a medical-surgical unit. Wallace Peterson, a 69-year-old male, was admitted to Room 327 with community-acquired pneumonia on a background of COPD. He is currently on supplemental oxygen via nasal cannula. The oncoming shift has just begun.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📋 Handoff Report</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Patient</th><td>Wallace Peterson</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Age / Gender</th><td>69 years · Male</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Room</th><td>327 · Provider: L. Myer, MD</td></tr>
            <tr><th>BMI / Weight</th><td>20.5 (underweight) · 131 lbs</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Primary Dx</th><td>Pneumonia (community-acquired)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Secondary Dx</th><td>COPD (Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Allergies</th><td>No Known Drug Allergies</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Code Status</th><td>Full Code</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Vitals on Admission</th><td>T 101°F · RR 28 · HR 106 · BP 148/82 · SpO2 90%</td></tr>
            <tr><th>O2</th><td>Nasal cannula in place</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💊 Medications on MAR</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li><strong>Dextrose 5% in ½ Normal Saline (D5½NS)</strong> — IV maintenance</li>
          <li><strong>Ipratropium (Atrovent) 18 mcg/puff MDI</strong> — Inhaled bronchodilator for COPD</li>
          <li><strong>Acetaminophen</strong> — PO PRN fever/discomfort</li>
          <li><strong>Hydrochlorothiazide (HCTZ)</strong> — PO for hypertension</li>
          <li><strong>Metoprolol</strong> — PO for hypertension/cardiac management</li>
          <li><strong>Ceftriaxone 500 mg</strong> — IM for bacterial pneumonia</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🚪 Entering the Room — What You Observe</h3>
      <p>Wallace is sitting up in bed appearing agitated and restless. His nasal cannula is in place. He looks fatigued and is breathing rapidly. He says, "I can't catch my breath and I feel awful." His skin is warm and diaphoretic.</p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: How does COPD complicate the management of pneumonia? What is the hypoxic drive concern?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>COPD + Pneumonia Interaction:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>COPD causes chronic air trapping and reduced alveolar surface area — pneumonia further reduces gas exchange capacity</li>
          <li>Combined effect: significantly worsened hypoxemia and increased work of breathing</li>
          <li>COPD patients may already be in a state of chronic hypercapnia (CO2 retention)</li>
          <li>Pneumonia can trigger an acute exacerbation of COPD (AECOPD)</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Hypoxic Drive in COPD:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>In healthy individuals, rising CO2 is the primary stimulus to breathe</li>
          <li>In chronic COPD: prolonged CO2 elevation desensitizes central chemoreceptors</li>
          <li>The brain may shift to relying on <strong>low O2 levels</strong> (hypoxic drive) to stimulate breathing</li>
          <li><strong>Clinical implication:</strong> Giving too much supplemental oxygen can suppress the hypoxic drive and cause respiratory depression</li>
          <li><strong>Target SpO2 for COPD patients: 88–92%</strong> — NOT the standard ≥95%</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ After your initial assessment, you perform a focused respiratory evaluation…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 2 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase2">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 2</span>
      <h2>Respiratory Assessment</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You complete a focused respiratory assessment of Wallace. His breathing is labored and he is using accessory muscles. You auscultate his lungs and document your findings.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📊 Vital Signs with Clinical Interpretation</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Vital Sign</th><th>Value</th><th>Significance</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Temperature</td><td>101°F</td><td class="text-danger">Fever — active infection</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Respiratory Rate</td><td>28 breaths/min</td><td class="text-danger">Tachypnea — respiratory distress</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Heart Rate</td><td>106 bpm</td><td class="text-danger">Tachycardia — compensatory response</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Blood Pressure</td><td>148/82 mmHg</td><td>Elevated — hypertension history</td></tr>
            <tr><td>SpO2</td><td>90%</td><td class="text-danger">Hypoxemia — critical finding</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🫁 Lung Assessment Findings</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Right Base</th><td>Diminished breath sounds with crackles (rales)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Left Lung</th><td>Reduced but present breath sounds</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Work of Breathing</th><td>Increased — accessory muscle use noted</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Cough</th><td>Productive, yellow-green sputum</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Position</th><td>Head of bed elevated 30–45°</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: What do these respiratory findings mean, and what are your priority nursing actions?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Interpreting the Findings:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>RR 28:</strong> Tachypnea indicates the body is working hard to maintain oxygenation — the respiratory muscles are tiring</li>
          <li><strong>SpO2 90%:</strong> Below the normal threshold of ≥95%; for a COPD patient the target is 88–92% — currently at the low end</li>
          <li><strong>Crackles at right base:</strong> Fluid/exudate in alveoli from pneumonia consolidation — impairing gas exchange</li>
          <li><strong>Tachycardia 106:</strong> Compensatory response to hypoxemia — heart pumping faster to deliver more O2</li>
          <li><strong>Fever 101°F:</strong> Increases metabolic oxygen demand, worsening the overall hypoxemia</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Priority Nursing Actions:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li>Verify nasal cannula is connected and patent — check tubing from wall to patient</li>
          <li>Confirm O2 flow rate is appropriate (1–3 L/min for COPD; target SpO2 88–92%)</li>
          <li>Notify provider of respiratory assessment findings</li>
          <li>Prepare to administer ordered medications (Ipratropium MDI, Ceftriaxone, Acetaminophen)</li>
          <li>Position HOB 30–45° to maximize diaphragmatic excursion</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ During a transfer maneuver, a crisis develops with the oxygen delivery…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 3 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase3">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 3</span>
      <h2>O2 Delivery — Disconnection Crisis</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">While repositioning Wallace in bed, the nasal cannula tubing becomes inadvertently disconnected from the wall oxygen source. Wallace's SpO2 begins to drop rapidly and he becomes increasingly combative and difficult to redirect.</p>
    <div class="callout callout-danger">
      <strong>🚨 Emergency: Oxygen Disconnected</strong>
      <p>Combativeness in a hypoxic patient is a <strong>late sign of CNS oxygen deprivation</strong> — not agitation or confusion. This is a medical emergency. Reconnect oxygen IMMEDIATELY before any other intervention.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>⚡ Immediate Response Steps</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Step 1</th><td>Recognize disconnected O2 tubing — trace from wall to patient</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Step 2</th><td>Reconnect nasal cannula to the oxygen source immediately</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Step 3</th><td>Verify O2 flow rate is set to ordered rate (1–3 L/min for COPD)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Step 4</th><td>Check all connections — wall outlet → tubing → nasal prongs</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Step 5</th><td>Reassess SpO2 — expect improvement within minutes of reconnection</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Step 6</th><td>Reassess Wallace — is he calming as oxygenation improves?</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🌬️ Oxygen Delivery Devices — Comparison</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Device</th><th>Flow Rate</th><th>FiO2 Delivered</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Nasal Cannula</td><td>1–6 L/min</td><td>24–44%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Simple Face Mask</td><td>6–10 L/min</td><td>35–50%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Venturi Mask</td><td>4–12 L/min</td><td>24–50% (precise)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Non-Rebreather Mask</td><td>10–15 L/min</td><td>60–90%</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🎯 COPD-Specific O2 Target</h3>
      <p><strong>Target SpO2 for COPD patients: 88–92%</strong> — Do NOT target ≥95% as in a healthy patient. Maintaining SpO2 above 92% risks suppressing the hypoxic drive and causing CO2 retention with respiratory depression. Use the lowest effective flow rate.</p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Explain the COPD hypoxic drive — why is too much oxygen dangerous?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Normal respiratory drive:</strong> Rising CO2 (hypercapnia) → stimulates central chemoreceptors → increases ventilation</p>
        <p><strong>COPD altered drive:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Chronic CO2 retention in COPD gradually desensitizes the central chemoreceptors to CO2</li>
          <li>The peripheral chemoreceptors (aortic/carotid bodies) become more sensitive to <em>low</em> O2</li>
          <li>In some COPD patients, <strong>hypoxemia becomes the primary drive to breathe</strong></li>
          <li>If you correct SpO2 to 99–100% with high-flow O2, you remove that hypoxic stimulus → respiratory rate slows → CO2 accumulates further → respiratory acidosis → CO2 narcosis → respiratory failure</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Signs of CO2 narcosis:</strong> Somnolence → confusion → loss of consciousness → respiratory arrest</p>
        <p><strong>Safe practice:</strong> Titrate O2 to maintain SpO2 88–92% in COPD patients; reassess frequently</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ With oxygen restored, you proceed to medication administration…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 4 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase4">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 4</span>
      <h2>Medication Administration</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You prepare to administer Wallace's ordered medications: Ceftriaxone 500 mg IM for pneumonia, Ipratropium MDI for COPD bronchodilation, and Acetaminophen for fever. You also review his home medications — HCTZ and Metoprolol — for safe administration.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💉 Ceftriaxone 500 mg IM — Administration</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Route</th><td>Intramuscular (IM)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Site</th><td>Vastus lateralis or ventrogluteal preferred</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Needle</th><td>21–23 gauge, 1–1.5 inch</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Technique</th><td>Z-track method — prevents medication leakage into subcutaneous tissue</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Allergy check</th><td>Ask about penicillin allergy (~1–2% cross-reactivity)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Volume</th><td>Reconstitute per label; typically &lt;3 mL per site</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🫁 Ipratropium MDI — Patient Technique</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Step 1</th><td>Shake the inhaler well before each puff</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Step 2</th><td>Exhale fully before positioning inhaler</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Step 3</th><td>Seal lips around mouthpiece</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Step 4</th><td>Inhale slowly and deeply while pressing down</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Step 5</th><td>Hold breath for 10 seconds before exhaling</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Step 6</th><td>Wait 1–2 minutes between puffs</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Step 7</th><td>Rinse mouth after use</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-warning">
      <strong>⚠️ Hold Parameters — HCTZ and Metoprolol</strong>
      <p><strong>Metoprolol (beta-blocker):</strong> Hold if HR &lt; 60 bpm or SBP &lt; 90 mmHg. Assess apical pulse × 1 minute before giving. Use with caution in COPD — beta-blockers can cause bronchospasm.<br/>
      <strong>HCTZ (diuretic):</strong> Check BP and potassium level before giving. Monitor for signs of dehydration — Wallace's BMI 20.5 indicates he is already underweight and potentially volume-depleted.</p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: What is the rationale for each medication in this scenario?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Medication</th><th>Rationale in This Patient</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>Ceftriaxone 500 mg IM</strong></td><td>3rd-generation cephalosporin — covers Streptococcus pneumoniae and Haemophilus influenzae, common CAP organisms; treats the bacterial source of infection</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Ipratropium MDI</strong></td><td>Anticholinergic bronchodilator — blocks muscarinic receptors → bronchodilation; addresses bronchoconstriction component of COPD; does NOT suppress hypoxic drive</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Acetaminophen</strong></td><td>Antipyretic — reduces fever (101°F), which decreases metabolic O2 demand; analgesic — promotes comfort and cooperation with breathing exercises</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>D5½NS IV</strong></td><td>Hydration maintenance — pneumonia increases insensible losses (fever, tachypnea); thins secretions to facilitate clearance</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>HCTZ / Metoprolol</strong></td><td>Chronic hypertension management — assess vital signs before each dose; consider holding if hemodynamically unstable</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Wallace is stabilizing — you begin patient and family education…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 5 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase5">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 5</span>
      <h2>Patient Education</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Wallace's SpO2 has improved to 91% following oxygen reconnection and medication administration. His RR has decreased slightly to 24. He is more alert. You take the opportunity to provide education on COPD management, oxygen safety, and pneumonia recovery.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🏠 COPD &amp; O2 Safety at Home</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Never remove nasal cannula without provider guidance</strong> — even if you feel better</li>
          <li>Oxygen is a fire hazard — no smoking, open flames, or aerosol sprays nearby</li>
          <li>Target SpO2 88–92% at home — not 95%+ as for general patients</li>
          <li>Report if breathing worsens, lips turn blue, or you become confused</li>
          <li>Keep O2 tubing clear of pathways — fall prevention</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💊 Inhaler Technique &amp; Smoking Cessation</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Shake inhaler, exhale first, inhale slowly, hold 10 seconds</li>
          <li>Rinse mouth after steroid inhalers to prevent thrush</li>
          <li>Use a spacer if coordination is difficult</li>
          <li><strong>Smoking cessation is the single most important intervention</strong> to slow COPD progression</li>
          <li>Resources: nicotine replacement therapy, varenicline, counseling</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🍽️ Nutrition</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>BMI 20.5 — underweight; poor nutrition impairs immune function and healing</li>
          <li>Small, frequent meals — large meals elevate the diaphragm and worsen dyspnea</li>
          <li>High-protein, high-calorie foods — eggs, nuts, cheese, whole milk</li>
          <li>Rest before meals to conserve energy for eating</li>
          <li>Nutritional consult if weight loss continues</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🚨 When to Seek Emergency Care</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Severe shortness of breath at rest</li>
          <li>Lips or fingertips turning blue (cyanosis)</li>
          <li>Confusion, combativeness, or loss of consciousness</li>
          <li>SpO2 falls below 88% despite using O2</li>
          <li>Chest pain, productive cough with bloody sputum</li>
          <li>Fever above 103°F or severe chills/rigors</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: How do you apply the teach-back method for Wallace's education?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Teach-Back Method — Principles:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>After explaining a concept, ask the patient to repeat it back in their own words — NOT "Do you understand?"</li>
          <li>Frame it as your responsibility: "I want to make sure I explained this clearly. Can you tell me what you will do if your oxygen tubing falls out at home?"</li>
          <li>Correct misunderstandings without judgment — re-teach using different words or visuals</li>
          <li>Limit to 2–3 key teaching points per session — avoid information overload</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Priority teach-back topics for Wallace:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li>MDI technique — have him demonstrate with the inhaler</li>
          <li>SpO2 target and what to do if alarm sounds at home</li>
          <li>Signs of worsening — when to call vs. go to ER</li>
          <li>Complete the full antibiotic course even when feeling better</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You complete your documentation and prioritize nursing diagnoses…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 6 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase6">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 6</span>
      <h2>Priority Nursing Diagnoses + SBAR</h2>
    </div>
    <h3>📋 Priority Nursing Diagnoses</h3>
    <div class="dx-rank-list">
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">1</span>
        <div><strong>Impaired Gas Exchange</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: SpO2 90%, RR 28/min, tachycardia HR 106, fever, productive cough, and inadvertent O2 disconnection — highest priority, patient is actively hypoxic</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">2</span>
        <div><strong>Ineffective Airway Clearance</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: crackles at right base, productive cough with yellow-green sputum, diminished breath sounds — COPD + pneumonia combination impairs secretion clearance</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">3</span>
        <div><strong>Activity Intolerance</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: dyspnea with exertion, tachycardia, fatigue, hypoxemia on supplemental oxygen</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">4</span>
        <div><strong>Deficient Knowledge</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: unfamiliarity with COPD O2 targets, inhaler technique, and home oxygen safety precautions</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">5</span>
        <div><strong>Risk for Infection (Complications)</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: age 69, COPD comorbidity, underweight BMI 20.5, and bacteremia/sepsis risk from untreated CAP</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ SBAR — Calling the Provider About Wallace's Respiratory Status</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <div class="sbar-block">
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-s"><span class="sbar-label">S — Situation</span><p>I am calling about Wallace Peterson in Room 327, a 69-year-old male admitted with community-acquired pneumonia and COPD. His nasal cannula became disconnected during repositioning and his SpO2 dropped significantly. I have reconnected the oxygen, but I am concerned about his ongoing respiratory status.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-b"><span class="sbar-label">B — Background</span><p>Admitted with CAP on a background of COPD. Vital signs on admission: T 101°F, RR 28, HR 106, BP 148/82, SpO2 90%. Currently receiving D5½NS, Ipratropium MDI, HCTZ, Metoprolol, and Ceftriaxone. BMI 20.5 — underweight.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-a"><span class="sbar-label">A — Assessment</span><p>Post-reconnection SpO2 is now 91%. RR has improved slightly to 24. He is more alert but remains tachycardic at 102. Crackles persist at the right lung base. He was combative during the hypoxic episode — consistent with late CNS hypoxia. I have administered the ordered Ipratropium MDI and Acetaminophen. Ceftriaxone IM has been given.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-r"><span class="sbar-label">R — Recommendation</span><p>Requesting confirmation of the appropriate O2 flow rate target for this COPD patient (currently at 2 L/min targeting SpO2 88–92%). Also requesting review of current antibiotic adequacy and consideration of ABG to assess ventilation and acid-base status.</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX A: Medications -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-a">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix A</span>
      <h2>Medication Review</h2>
    </div>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Medication</th><th>Class</th><th>Key Nursing Points</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Ceftriaxone (Rocephin) 500 mg IM</strong></td>
          <td>3rd-generation cephalosporin antibiotic</td>
          <td>Inhibits bacterial cell wall synthesis; covers S. pneumoniae and H. influenzae; assess for penicillin/cephalosporin allergy (1–2% cross-reactivity); use Z-track IM technique; monitor for rash, GI upset, injection site reaction</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Ipratropium (Atrovent) 18 mcg/puff MDI</strong></td>
          <td>Anticholinergic bronchodilator</td>
          <td>Blocks muscarinic receptors → bronchodilation; used for COPD maintenance; shake before use; hold breath 10 seconds; wait 1–2 min between puffs; rinse mouth; adverse effects: dry mouth, urinary retention, tachycardia</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Acetaminophen (Tylenol)</strong></td>
          <td>Analgesic / Antipyretic</td>
          <td>Reduces fever (decreases metabolic O2 demand); PRN — assess temperature before giving; max 4 g/day; caution in hepatic disease; monitor for continued fever elevation</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Hydrochlorothiazide (HCTZ)</strong></td>
          <td>Thiazide diuretic / Antihypertensive</td>
          <td>Check BP and K⁺ before giving; risk of hypokalemia; monitor I&amp;O; administer in morning; patient already underweight — assess for dehydration; report dizziness</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Metoprolol (Lopressor)</strong></td>
          <td>Beta-1 selective adrenergic blocker</td>
          <td>Hold if HR &lt; 60 or SBP &lt; 90; assess apical pulse × 1 minute before giving; use caution in COPD — beta-blockers can cause bronchospasm; do not abruptly discontinue; monitor for fatigue, bradycardia</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>D5½NS (Dextrose 5% in 0.45% NaCl)</strong></td>
          <td>Hypotonic IV maintenance fluid</td>
          <td>Provides maintenance hydration and glucose; helps thin secretions; monitor IV site, I&amp;O, lung sounds for fluid overload; ensure correct flow rate per order</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX B: Q&A -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-b">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Post-Simulation Questions &amp; Answers</h2>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q1: Why is the target SpO2 for a COPD patient 88–92% and not ≥95%?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>Patients with chronic COPD may develop tolerance to elevated CO2 levels over time. Their central chemoreceptors become desensitized to CO2, and some patients shift to relying on peripheral chemoreceptors that respond to <strong>low oxygen</strong> as their primary stimulus to breathe (hypoxic drive). If supplemental oxygen raises their SpO2 to 99–100%, this hypoxic drive is eliminated, respirations slow, CO2 accumulates further, and <strong>CO2 narcosis with respiratory failure</strong> can result. Targeting SpO2 88–92% maintains adequate oxygenation without removing the breathing stimulus.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q2: The nasal cannula tubing appears connected but the patient's SpO2 is still low. What do you check?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Trace the entire O2 system:</strong> wall outlet → flow meter → tubing → nasal prongs — check every connection point</li>
          <li><strong>Flow meter:</strong> Is it set to the ordered flow rate? Is it actually turned on?</li>
          <li><strong>Nasal prongs:</strong> Are they positioned correctly in the nares or have they slipped out?</li>
          <li><strong>Tubing kinks:</strong> Is the tubing kinked, compressed under the patient, or caught under the bed rail?</li>
          <li><strong>Wall outlet:</strong> Is the flowmeter properly inserted and locked into the wall O2 outlet?</li>
          <li><strong>Patient:</strong> Is Wallace breathing through his mouth? Nasal cannula delivers little benefit if the patient is exclusively mouth-breathing</li>
          <li><strong>Alternative:</strong> If nasal cannula is insufficient, notify provider for consideration of a face mask or Venturi mask</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q3: Explain the pathophysiology of community-acquired pneumonia (CAP).</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Pathophysiology of CAP:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Infection:</strong> Bacteria (most commonly Streptococcus pneumoniae) invade the lower respiratory tract, overcoming normal defenses (cough, mucociliary clearance, alveolar macrophages)</li>
          <li><strong>Inflammatory response:</strong> Cytokines recruit neutrophils and inflammatory cells to the infected alveoli</li>
          <li><strong>Consolidation:</strong> Alveoli fill with exudate (fluid, WBCs, bacteria) — the lung becomes solid ("consolidated") rather than air-filled; this is seen as an opacity on chest X-ray</li>
          <li><strong>V/Q mismatch:</strong> Consolidated alveoli are perfused with blood but cannot participate in gas exchange (no airflow) → hypoxemia</li>
          <li><strong>Systemic effects:</strong> Fever, tachycardia, tachypnea, leukocytosis from the systemic inflammatory response</li>
        </ol>
        <p>In Wallace's case, COPD reduces his baseline reserve, making the V/Q mismatch far more impactful than in a healthy patient.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q4: Why are elderly patients like Wallace more susceptible to pneumonia and its complications?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Immunosenescence:</strong> Aging impairs immune function — reduced neutrophil activity, lower antibody production, diminished T-cell response</li>
          <li><strong>Reduced mucociliary clearance:</strong> Ciliary function declines with age — less ability to clear pathogens and secretions from the airways</li>
          <li><strong>Weakened respiratory muscles:</strong> Less effective cough, reduced ability to clear secretions</li>
          <li><strong>Comorbidities:</strong> COPD, heart disease, diabetes compound the impairment in gas exchange</li>
          <li><strong>Atypical presentation:</strong> Elderly patients may have minimal fever and less productive cough — instead presenting with confusion, weakness, and falls</li>
          <li><strong>Malnutrition:</strong> Wallace's BMI 20.5 (underweight) impairs immune function and healing</li>
          <li><strong>Higher complication risk:</strong> Bacteremia, sepsis, ARDS, and respiratory failure all occur at higher rates in elderly patients</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q5: What is your approach to fever management in Wallace, and when would you withhold acetaminophen?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Fever management principles:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Fever increases metabolic oxygen demand — each 1°C rise in temperature increases O2 consumption by ~13%</li>
          <li>In a patient already hypoxic (SpO2 90%), reducing fever directly improves oxygen balance</li>
          <li>Acetaminophen 650–1000 mg PO is first-line for fever in this patient</li>
          <li>Cooling measures (cool compresses, tepid sponge bath) are adjuncts for comfort</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>When to withhold acetaminophen:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>History of hepatic disease or liver failure — acetaminophen is hepatotoxic in overdose</li>
          <li>Recent alcohol use — increases hepatotoxicity risk</li>
          <li>Maximum daily dose already reached (4 g/day total from all sources — check combination products)</li>
          <li>Allergy to acetaminophen</li>
          <li>Temperature is already below 100.4°F and the PRN indication is not met</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

